### F7 - BBV emission plugin (profile mode)

- Status: done. `qemu_plugin/bbv_emit.{c,h}` provides a self-contained
  SimPoint-format emitter (PC -> bb_id hash, per-slice flush, sparse
  rows matching the SimPoint 3.2 sample.bb convention). Plugin args
  `bbv_out=PATH,slice=N` register a per-insn callback that ticks the
  emitter; it is registered BEFORE the icount callback so when both
  fire on the same insn (icount target == slice multiple) the slice
  row is durable before exit(200). The shipped SimPoint binary
  (F12) parses the emitted file without error. Verified end-to-end:
  on icount_spin with ICOUNT=1M,SLICE=10k, SimPoint identifies 2
  phases (startup weight 0.01, steady-state loop weight 0.99) which
  matches the workload's structure.
- Type: behavioral
- Description: BBV emission as a second sub-mode of `hybrid_handoff`
  (not a separate plugin - keeps per-insn callback cost to one
  per insn). New plugin args `bbv_out=PATH,slice=N`. Emit one BBV row
  per `slice` dynamic insns into a SimPoint-readable `.bb` file.
- Key files:
  - `qemu_plugin/hybrid_handoff.c`
  - `qemu_plugin/bbv_emit.c` (new sub-module)
  - `qemu_plugin/bbv_emit.h` (new)
  - `qemu_plugin/Makefile`
  - `hybrid_vsim/tests/hybrid/test_plugin_bbv_emit.sh` (new)
- Dependencies: F5 (reuses the per-insn callback path)
- TDD RED: `tests/hybrid/test_plugin_bbv_emit.sh` runs icount_spin
  with `bbv_out=/tmp/x.bb,slice=1000,icount=10000`; asserts the file
  has exactly 10 SimPoint-format rows and the SimPoint binary parses
  it. Failed pre-implementation because the plugin rejected
  `bbv_out=` as an unknown option.

