### F11 - BBV slice-consume trigger

- Status: done. Plugin args `slice=N,slice_at=K` add a third sub-mode
  to `hybrid_handoff` (alongside CSR/PC, icount, BBV-emit). A
  per-insn callback counts retired insns into a slice accumulator;
  on every Nth insn the slice index advances. When the slice index
  exceeds the target `slice_at=K` (0-based), drain fires via the
  same `on_handoff` path. Reuses the existing `slice=` parameter so
  BBV-emit and slice-consume share one source of truth for slice
  size. Plugin emits a deterministic `idx=K+1 target=K` stderr line
  at drain so the e2e test can verify timing without relying on
  `minstret` (which is a cycle-counter proxy on andes-ax45mpv).
  Orchestrator-side `phase` trigger kind in `plan.py` is deferred
  to the F8 N-way wave -- F11's plugin contract stands alone and
  the test invokes the plugin directly with `slice=N,slice_at=K`.
- Type: behavioral
- Description: Third sub-mode of `hybrid_handoff` (after CSR/PC,
  icount, BBV-emit): read a slice-index list, fire drain when the
  icount counter hits each slice index. Orchestrator chains N
  invocations through the plan grammar to produce K archived regions
  per SimPoint cluster.
- Key files:
  - `qemu_plugin/hybrid_handoff.c`
  - `qemu_plugin/bbv_emit.c`
  - `hybrid_vsim/tests/hybrid/test_plugin_phase_consume.sh` (new)
  - `tools/orchestrator/plan.py` (new trigger kind `phase`; deferred
    to F8)
- Dependencies: F5, F7, F12 (slice indices come from SimPoint's
  output file), F8 (only the orchestrator-chaining piece)
- TDD RED: `tests/hybrid/test_plugin_phase_consume.sh` runs
  icount_spin with `slice=1000,slice_at=2`; asserts QEMU exits 200,
  the plugin's drain log reads `idx=3 target=2`, and the drained PC
  is inside the icount_spin loop body. Failed pre-implementation
  because the plugin rejected `slice_at=` as an unknown option.

### F12 - SimPoint binary integration

- Status: done. SimPoint 3.2 added as a git submodule at
  `tools/simpoint/` pinned to upstream commit `17783e5`. Builds via
  `build_simpoint.sh` (or `source setup.sh` step 4/4) and produces
  `tools/simpoint/bin/simpoint` under g++ 14.2.1 with no patches.
  Verified the binary parses both the shipped `input/sample.bb` and
  a real BBV emitted by F7 (icount_spin at 1M insns, slice=10k);
  output cleanly separates the boot phase (weight 0.01) from the
  steady-state loop (weight 0.99). The F7 e2e test
  `test_plugin_bbv_emit.sh` invokes the binary via `SIMPOINT_BIN`
  (default `tools/simpoint/bin/simpoint`) every run, guarding the
  BBV/SimPoint contract.
- Type: structural (external tool integration; no first-party code
  changed)
- Description: Bring SimPoint 3.2 in-tree under `tools/simpoint/`
  (submodule) so the BBV pipeline (F7 -> F12 -> F11) has a single
  canonical clustering binary; the orchestrator's eventual
  `simpoint` subcommand invokes it. SimPoint output
  (`<slice_idx> <cluster_id>` rows in `*.simpts`,
  `<weight> <cluster_id>` rows in `*.weights`) becomes the feed for
  F11.
- Key files:
  - `.gitmodules` (submodule registration)
  - `tools/simpoint/` (submodule:
    https://github.com/OscarLGH/SimPoint.3.2)
  - `build_simpoint.sh` (host build script)
  - `setup.sh` (step 4/4 + clean simpoint target)
  - `hybrid_vsim/tests/hybrid/test_plugin_bbv_emit.sh` (sources
    `SIMPOINT_BIN`)
- Dependencies: F7
- TDD RED: covered by F7's `test_plugin_bbv_emit.sh` - the SimPoint
  parse step asserts non-empty simpts/weights output, fails if the
  binary is missing/broken.

